'11:7': [
{sup:1, word:"high", lines:["Places where the Gentile peoples worshipped their idols. When the children of Israel entered the land of Canaan to possess it, God commanded them to destroy all the high places of the nations ({Num33:52|Num. 33:52}). Here Solomon, the very one who had built the temple according to God&rsquo;s desire on the ground of the oneness of God&rsquo;s people, took the lead to build up the high places once again. These high places were related to fornication and idolatry. Solomon&rsquo;s setting up of the high places was especially connected with the indulgence of lust in his loving many foreign women. See {1Ki12:31^2|note 31<sup>2</sup>} in {1Ki12|ch. 12}."]},
],
'11:9': [
{sup:1, word:"So", lines:["After Solomon fell, God came in to punish and discipline him. God became angry with Solomon and determined to tear the kingdom away from him and give it to his servant (vv. {1Ki11:9|9}-{1Ki11:13|13}). For David&rsquo;s sake, however, God would not do this in Solomon&rsquo;s days but would do it in the days of his son (vv. {1Ki11:12|12}, {1Ki11:34|34}). Moreover, for David&rsquo;s sake and for the sake of Jerusalem, which God had chosen, God would still keep one tribe for the son of Solomon (vv. {1Ki11:13|13}, {1Ki11:32|32}-{1Ki11:33|33}, {1Ki11:35|35}-{1Ki11:36|36})."]},
{sup:"a", word:"appeared", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Kings 3:5; 9:2; 2&nbsp;Chron. 1:7"},
],
'11:11': [
{sup:"a", word:"tear", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Kings 11:31, 35; 14:8"},
],
'11:13': [
{sup:1, word:"one", lines:["The kingdom of God&rsquo;s elect was split into two: the southern kingdom, the kingdom of Judah, of two tribes and the northern kingdom, the kingdom of Israel, of ten tribes (vv. {1Ki11:30|30}-{1Ki11:32|32}). Judah was genuine, but Israel was a division in apostasy. The division among God&rsquo;s elect issued in confusion, which always accompanies division ({Gen11:7|Gen. 11:7}-{Gen11:9|9}). See {Mat1:7^1|note 7<sup>1</sup>} in {Mat1|Matt. 1}."]},
{sup:"a", word:"tribe", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Kings 11:32, 36; 12:20"},
],
